    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is tinnitus?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Tinnitus is the perception of sound — such as ringing, buzzing, hissing, clicking, or humming — when no external sound source is present. It is not a disease itself but a symptom, most commonly caused by damage to the hair cells in the inner ear, which triggers the brain to generate phantom noise to compensate for lost auditory input."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What causes tinnitus?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The most common cause of tinnitus is hearing loss — either from noise exposure or natural aging (presbycusis). When the hair cells in the cochlea are damaged, they stop sending signals to the auditory cortex. The brain, deprived of input, increases its own neural activity, generating phantom sound. Other causes include ear infections, earwax blockage, head injuries, certain medications (ototoxic drugs), and cardiovascular conditions."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Is tinnitus curable?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "There is currently no universal cure for tinnitus, but it is highly manageable. Many patients experience significant relief — and some achieve complete elimination of perceived sound — through clinically validated treatments like Signia Notch Therapy."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is Signia Notch Therapy and does it work?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Signia Notch Therapy is a patented, evidence-based tinnitus treatment built into Signia hearing aids. A specialist first identifies the exact pitch (frequency) of the patient's tinnitus. The hearing aid is then programmed to amplify all sounds except that specific frequency, creating a notch. Over time, the brain learns to deprioritize the tinnitus tone. Clinical studies show Notch Therapy achieves approximately 89% patient satisfaction, compared to 42% for traditional masking."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Why doesn't white noise masking cure tinnitus?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "White noise masking covers tinnitus temporarily by introducing external sound to compete with the phantom noise. However, it does not retrain the brain or address the underlying auditory deprivation. When the masking sound is removed, the tinnitus returns — often seeming louder. Notch Therapy works differently by targeting the neurological mechanism that generates the tinnitus signal."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Can hearing aids help with tinnitus?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Yes. Hearing aids — especially those equipped with Signia Notch Therapy — address tinnitus through two mechanisms: they restore auditory input, reducing the brain's need to generate phantom noise; and Notch Therapy actively retrains the brain's response to the tinnitus frequency."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What are the warning signs of tinnitus?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The primary warning sign is perceiving sound — ringing, buzzing, hissing, clicking, whistling, or humming — in one or both ears without any external source. Secondary signs include sleep disruption, difficulty concentrating, heightened anxiety, emotional distress, and avoidance of quiet environments. If tinnitus is sudden, unilateral, or accompanied by hearing loss or dizziness, seek medical evaluation immediately."
        }
      }
    ]
  }
