            <div>
              <h3 style="color:#fff; font-family:'Lora',serif; font-size:1.4rem; margin-bottom:16px;">How the Hearing System Works</h3>
              <p style="color:#bfdbfe; font-size:0.95rem;">In a healthy ear, thousands of microscopic hair cells in the cochlea convert sound vibrations into electrical signals sent to the auditory cortex. Each hair cell is tuned to a specific frequency.</p>
              <p style="color:#bfdbfe; font-size:0.95rem;">When these hair cells are damaged — by noise exposure, aging, or other factors — they stop sending their signals. The auditory cortex detects this silence and responds.</p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <h3 style="color:#fff; font-family:'Lora',serif; font-size:1.4rem; margin-bottom:16px;">Why the Brain Creates Phantom Sound</h3>
              <p style="color:#bfdbfe; font-size:0.95rem;">The brain is wired to expect continuous auditory input. When it stops receiving signals at certain frequencies, it increases its own neural activity — essentially "turning up the gain" — trying to detect the missing sounds.</p>
              <p style="color:#bfdbfe; font-size:0.95rem;">This hyperactivity in the auditory cortex is perceived as sound even when none exists externally. <strong style="color:#fff;">That phantom perception is tinnitus.</strong></p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="brain-box reveal">
            <div class="b-icon">🔊</div>
            <p>Your brain, craving auditory input, <strong>"turns up the volume"</strong> to find the missing signal. When it cannot find it, it creates its own noise to fill the silence. That self-generated noise is your tinnitus — and it can be retrained.</p>
